{{other uses}} {{Refimprove|date=February 2017}} In [[discourse]]-based grammatical theory, '''information flow''' is any tracking of [[reference|referential]] information by speakers. Information may be ''new,'' just introduced into the conversation; ''given,'' already active in the speakers' consciousness; or ''old,'' no longer active.<ref>{{cite book |last=Chafe |first=Wallace |editor-last=Li |editor-first=Charles |title=Subject and topic |publisher=Academic Presss |date=1976 |pages=25–55 |chapter=Givenness, contrastiveness, definiteness, subjects, topics, and point of view}}</ref> The various types of activation, and how these are defined, are model-dependent.
Information flow affects grammatical structures such as: *[[word order]] ([[topic (linguistics)|topic]], [[focus (linguistics)|focus]], and [[wikt:afterthought|afterthought]] constructions). *active, passive, or middle [[Grammatical voice|voice]]. *choice of [[deixis]], such as [[article (grammar)|articles]]; "medial" deictics such as [[Spanish language|Spanish]] ''ese'' and [[Japanese language|Japanese]] ''sore'' are generally determined by the familiarity of a referent rather than by physical distance{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}}. *overtness of information, such as whether an [[Verb argument|argument]] of a [[verb]] is indicated by a [[lexical (semiotics)|lexical]] [[noun phrase]], a [[pronoun]], or not mentioned at all. *Clefting: Splitting a single clause into two clauses, each with its own verb, e.g. ‘The [[chicken turtle]]s tasted like chicken.’ becomes ‘It was the chicken turtle | that tasted like chicken.’ In this case, clefting is used to shift the focus of the sentence to the subject, chicken turtle. *Front Focus: Placing at the start (front) of a sentence information that would normally occur later in the sentence, to give it extra prominence. For example, in pop culture, [[Yoda|Grand Master of the Jedi Order]] Yoda's speech often utilises such syntactic construction, such as when he says 'much to learn you still have' to [[Luke Skywalker]]. *End Focus (End Weight): Given or familiar information followed by new information. This gives prominence to the final part of the sentences and can enable suspense to build, e.g. ‘Through the door came a gigantic wolf’.(Umer Prince)
