The '''Majorville Cairn and Medicine Wheel''' (''Iniskim Umaapi'') is an archaeological site of the [[Blackfeet Nation]] located south of [[Bassano, Alberta]]. The [[medicine wheel]] has been dated to 3200 BCE (5200 years ago) by careful [[stratification (archeology)|stratification]] of known artifact types.<ref>The Majorville Cairn and Medicine Wheel Site, James M Calder, National Museum of Man Series, Archaeology Survey of Canada No. 62, Ottawa, 1977</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://wyoshpo.state.wy.us/medwheel.htm |title=Medicine Wheel National Historic Landmark |accessdate=2008-01-05 |work= |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080125062135/http://wyoshpo.state.wy.us/medwheel.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-01-25}}</ref>
The medicine wheel sits on top of a grassy hill at an elevation of 918 m<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://webapp.geod.nrcan.gc.ca/geod/data-donnees/station/report-rapport.php?id=26615 |title=Rocky Butte Station Report |publisher=Natural Resources Canada |access-date=September 10, 2017}}</ref> overlooking a large area of undisturbed prairie around the Bow River. The structure consists of a round stone cairn, 9 m in diameter, surrounded by a 27 m wide cobble circle connected to the cairn by 28 stone spokes. This arrangement is categorized as Subgroup 6 and of the total 67 known medicine wheels only 3 belong to this category, the other two being the Jennings site in South Dakota and [[Medicine Wheel/Medicine Mountain National Historic Landmark|Bighorn]] in Wyoming.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://hermis.alberta.ca/ARHP/Details.aspx?DeptID=1&ObjectID=4665-0042 |title=Majorville Cairn and Medicine Wheel |publisher=HeRMIS |access-date=September 10, 2017}}</ref>
The southern half of the cairn has been excavated and the projectile points found indicate it was in use since the Oxbow/McKean Phase for the last 4500 years. The site was built in layers, with the earliest [[Radiocarbon dating|{{chem|14|C}}]] date from the cairn determined at 3845 plus/minus 85 radiocarbon years before present.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=15835&pid=0 |title=Majorville Cairn and Medicine Wheel |publisher=Canada's Historic Places |access-date=September 10, 2017}}</ref> [[Calibration of radiocarbon dates|Calibrated]] to calendar years this is 2384 plus minus 124 years before 1950,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.calpal-online.de/ |title=Cologne Radiocarbon Calibration & Paleoclimate Research Package |publisher=[[Monrepos (archaeology)|Monrepos]] |access-date=September 10, 2017}}</ref> although this sample doesn't come from the earliest construction period.
Among the stones were found offerings in the form of [[Hierochloe odorata|sweet grass]], willow, cloth and tobacco. The site further yielded ''iniskim'' stones ("buffalo calling stones"), fragments of [[ammonite]] fossils that can be found in the bedrock exposed by the Bow River to the east of the site.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/en/rep-reg/place-lieu.aspx?id=15835&pid=0 |title=Majorville Cairn and Medicine Wheel |publisher=Canada's Historic Places |access-date=September 10, 2017}}</ref> Iniskim are small natural stones that resemble the shoulders and hump of a buffalo.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bryan |first=Liz|date=2015 |title=Stone by Stone |edition=2nd |publisher=Heritage House Publishing Company |pages=63 |location=Canada |isbn=978-1-77203-050-1 |url= }}</ref> In this case the petrified coils of [[ammonite]] shells that broke along the septa into small figurines with four prongs on one side resembling legs. These have been used in the [[Blackfeet Nation]] folklore to secure the return of the migrating buffaloes.
